        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity:

From Pety et al. (2012), the peak C3H+ flux arising from the 12" bar in the 26" IRAM beam is ~540 mJy.  The 12" source size is determined from a 6" resolution map.  Therefore, the assumption of a completely smooth, homogenous 12" bar is the absolute worse-case scenario with respect to resolving out flux with the ALMA beam.  Even assuming this worst-case scenario (with the ALMA beam resolving out 99% of the flux to a peak intensity of ~5.4 mJy), the requested 2.5 mJy RMS still results in a ~2 sigma detection of the targeted C3H+ transition.  In reality, we expect this emitting region to be both more compact and, more importantly, clumpy.  This will greatly increase the final S/N of the detection.  The peak flux arising from the targeted C2H transitions is expected to be ~150 mJy in the worst-case scenario and will be readily detected at very high S/N.

Pety et al. (2012) find a linewidth of 0.8 km/s in this source.  Because we are not interested in excitation conditions or rigorous abundance measurements, but rather spatial distributions, well-resolved line shapes are not essential to our science.  Therefore, we have chosen a spectral resolution of ~0.4 km/s.  This will provide a few resolution elements across the full line - more than sufficient for accurate distribution maps - while greatly reducing the required integration time to achieve the necessary S/N.

Imaging:

Fig. 1 of the Science Justification shows a cartoon of the target region of the PDR.  While the overall region is quite large and extended, the ALMA main beam will cover a significant portion of the previously mapped region.  Additionally, the 30" recoverable scale greatly exceeds the previously measured 12" source width.  While it is possible we will lose some sensitivity to extremely extended structure in the bar at the outer edges of the observation, this will be minimal.  The additional time and overhead necessary to perform a mosaic map or use of the ACA to recover this would be an inefficient use of array time.  As it is, the request configuration will provide detailed maps of the main PDR, the PDR edge, the gas behind the PDR, and the dense core.  This provides full coverage of the region and processes of interest.  The entirety of the region of interest, with the exception of the dense core, fits well within the ALMA primary beam.  For all other regions, we anticipate no loss of sensitivity due to approaching the edges of the beam.  In the case of the dense core, while some sensitivity will likely be lost, the compact nature of this region will be better-matched to the 2" synthesized beam.  This should compensate for any loss in sensitivity at the beam edge.

Correlator Setup:

We have chosen our correlator setup to target the species outline in the Science Justification with sufficient spectral resolution while still remaining within standard data rate limits.  The requested setup covers C3H+ and the essential tracer molecules for comparison in the most data-efficient method possible.  

Calibration:

We have selected system-defined calibration as suggested.

Bandpass accuracy:

We anticipate no issues arising in this area, as the targeted features are narrow and the continuum is negligible compared to the line flux at these frequencies.

Scheduling/Time Constraints:

We require no special scheduling or time considerations.

Data rate:

We do not exceed the recommended data rate for these observations.

Special constraints:

Our total overheads constitute &lt;25% of the total observational time and have moderate integration times.</prj:justificationText>
