    <prp:abstract>Pety et al. (2012) have reported a series of unidentified transitions in mm-wave observations of the Horsehead photo-dissociation region (PDR) and, based on theoretical work, assigned these to the C3H+ cation.  Soon after, this assignment was question by Huang et al. (2012) and Fortenberry et al. (2013), who suggest the anion, C3H-, is a more likely candidate.  Subsequent observational studies by McGuire et al. (2013a &amp; 2013b), have detected this molecule, dubbed B11244, in Sgr B2(N), and find tentative observational evidence supporting the assignment of B11244 to C3H+.  A further survey of over three dozen sources (McGuire et al. 2014), however, has found only one additional detection.  This raises the question as to the, apparently extremely rare, environmental conditions necessary to produce B11244 in detectable abundance.  Here, we propose to map B11244 toward the Horsehead PDR to determine the precise physical and chemical environment which has given rise to this species.  These observations cannot be performed by any other facility - in fact, ALMA can perform this search three order of magnitude more efficiently than current-general facilities.</prp:abstract>
